Title: Elevation
Author: Stephen King
My Review: I have to admit, this was a great read after a King break. Forgot how good he is at quickly making you connecting with his characters, how instant and easy one can identify and emphatise with them. If you ever want to get someone hooked on King that is a bit squeamish, this is a great book. Lighter version of Thinner, happier implications.

Title: Arhanghelul Raul
Author: Ovidiu Eftimie
My Review:
O incercare foarte reusita de a copia un stil care inca nu se bucura de o foarte mare popularitate in romania, anume auto-ironia nationala cu ajutorul unei povesti gogomane in stil SF. Caragiale meets Douglas Adams si ghidul autostopistului galactic.
O lectura de o dupa-amiaza, usoara, amuzanta pe alocuri care castiga 5 stele in loc de 4 doar pentru originalitatea cu care l-a copiat pe Adams si a adaptat stereotipurile pentru Romania. Voi continua sa citesc lecturi mai serioase de la el cand imi voi pune mana pe el, este un autor cu potential.

My Review: Great fantasy to read, feels truly well documented and spares no detail in transporting you to that age. Was not a big fan of the ending but it did seem like the only possible outcome.

Title: Mindstar Rising (Greg Mandel, #1)
Author: Peter F. Hamilton
My Review:
Brilliantly paced book, can keep you hooked well into the night past your normal bedtime.
The distopian future it presents is really lightweight in terms of "wow" factor, which really makes it all the more real. The author does not dwell on it but it really helps build the overall picture and can really see it come into play and shape the actions of characters as well as the overall action of the book.
Not light but not excessively hard SF from the author of highly acclaimed space epics, a bit closer to home.
Definitely a read if you feel you need a classic scifi read, great actions and evolving characters and also how scary close we are to achieving the narative written almost two decades ago.

Title: The Future of Leadership: Rise of Automation, Robotics and Artificial Intelligence
Author: Brigette Tasha Hyacinth
My Review: Very good book, full of information about the field and explaining a lot of concepts and events. It is starting to not be as actual as one would want, but it is a good introduction. The leadership part was quite small and not that interesting or innovative. It did give a few good in-context pointers, that I really appreciated.

My Review: Really good to see the wide diversity of themes that were available in the long ago years. Great introduction with a lot of books being added to my wish list. Great stories, great authors!

Title: Big Data: A Revolution That Will Transform How We Live, Work, and Think
Author: Viktor Mayer-Sch√∂nberger
My Review: Really easy to understand some of the trends in big data, as valid in 2020 as they were in 2012 as well as some of the main paradigms behind them. Good lecture to get a better idea of the social theory of the field, not that deep in hard facts and technical data. More examples looking would have helped but considering the publication year, really impressive.

Title: Perihelion Summer
Author: Greg Egan
My Review: I enjoyed the fact that it was a stand alone book, was really quick to read and had enough of a story to hit all the sweet spots of a good read. The idea had some holes overall, and some of the concepts are not as developed as they could have been but well worth the read

Title: Zero Bomb
Author: M.T. Hill
My Review: The only thing that lifted the book to two stars was the fox. The action loses all hope of linearity, after doing 2 or 3 jumps across time, with no real value. No story finishes, although there is a great character development, when you get attached/empathise to either of the characters, it jumps to a different, really unrelated story. Has a vague concept of SF, but it is actually more like exploiting current technology with a twist.

Title: Sleeping Beauties
Author: Stephen King
My Review: Highly addictive as usual. I did enjoy the fact that different to most of his solo books, this one focuses on the outside perception of characters rather than on the inner reflection and the change is seen through the eyes of story participants rather than themselves. Nice change of style
